---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import {mutatorSidebar} from '../../../data/mutator-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
import {ultraVersion, ultraGroup, mavenCentralUrl} from '../../../data/site';
---

<DocsLayout title="Getting Started with Mutator" sidebar={mutatorSidebar}
            description="Set up Mutator with KSP in your Kotlin project">

    <h1>Getting Started</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Add Mutator to your project, annotate your data classes, and start mutating.
    </p>

    <h2>1. Add the dependencies</h2>

    <p>Mutator uses <a href="https://kotlinlang.org/docs/ksp-overview.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">KSP (Kotlin
        Symbol Processing)</a> to generate code at compile time. You need two dependencies: the runtime library and the
        KSP processor.</p>

    <p>In your <code>build.gradle.kts</code>:</p>

    <Code code={`plugins {
    id("com.google.devtools.ksp") version "<ksp-version>"
}

dependencies {
    // Runtime library
    implementation("${ultraGroup}:mutator-core:${ultraVersion}")
    // KSP processor — generates .mutator() and .mutate {} extensions
    ksp("${ultraGroup}:mutator-ksp:${ultraVersion}")
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>Find the latest version on <a href={mavenCentralUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Maven Central</a>.</p>

    <h2>2. Annotate your data classes</h2>

    <p>Add <code>@Mutable</code> to any data class you want to mutate:</p>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.mutator.Mutable

@Mutable
data class Address(
    val street: String,
    val city: String,
    val zip: String,
)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>Build your project. KSP generates extension functions for every <code>@Mutable</code> class:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><code>Address.mutator()</code> — creates a long-lived <code>Mutator&lt;Address&gt;</code></li>
        <li><code>Address.mutate {'{ ... }'}</code> — one-shot mutation, returns a new <code>Address</code></li>
        <li>Typed property setters: <code>mutator.street = "..."</code>, <code>mutator.city = "..."</code>, etc.</li>
        <li>Collection extensions: <code>List&lt;Address&gt;.mutator()</code>, <code>Set&lt;Address&gt;.mutator()</code>,
            <code>Map&lt;K, Address&gt;.mutator()</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>3. Your first mutation</h2>

    <p>The simplest way to use Mutator is the <code>mutate {'{ }'}</code> function. It creates a mutator, applies your
        changes, and returns a new immutable instance:</p>

    <Code code={`val address = Address(street = "123 Main St", city = "Springfield", zip = "62701")

val updated = address.mutate {
    street = "456 Oak Ave"
    city = "Shelbyville"
}

// updated == Address("456 Oak Ave", "Shelbyville", "62701")
// address is unchanged — still Address("123 Main St", "Springfield", "62701")`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>4. Nested mutations</h2>

    <p>When data classes reference other <code>@Mutable</code> data classes, their mutators compose automatically:</p>

    <Code code={`@Mutable
data class Person(
    val firstName: String,
    val lastName: String,
    val age: Int,
    val address: Address,
)

val person = Person(
    firstName = "John",
    lastName = "Doe",
    age = 42,
    address = Address(street = "Main St", city = "Springfield", zip = "62701")
)

// Nested mutation — no copy() chains
val updated = person.mutate {
    firstName = "Jane"
    address {
        street = "456 Oak Ave"
        city = "Shelbyville"
    }
}

// updated == Person("Jane", "Doe", 42, Address("456 Oak Ave", "Shelbyville", "62701"))`} lang="kotlin"
          theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>The <code>address {'{ }'}</code> block opens a sub-mutator. Any changes inside it automatically propagate back up
        to the parent <code>Person</code>.</p>

    <h2>5. Long-lived mutators</h2>

    <p>For form state management, you typically keep a mutator alive across multiple interactions:</p>

    <Code code={`val mutator = person.mutator()

// User edits the name field
mutator.firstName = "Jane"

// User edits the address
mutator.address.street = "456 Oak Ave"

// Check if anything changed
mutator.isModified()    // true

// Read the current state
val current = mutator()
// current == Person("Jane", "Doe", 42, Address("456 Oak Ave", "Springfield", "62701"))

// Save: accept changes as the new baseline
mutator.commit()
mutator.isModified()    // false`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>What KSP generates</h2>

    <p>For a data class like <code>Address</code>, KSP generates code equivalent to:</p>

    <Code code={`// Generated: mutator creator
fun Address.mutator() = ObjectMutator(this)

// Generated: one-shot mutation
fun Address.mutate(mutation: ObjectMutator<Address>.() -> Unit): Address =
    mutator().apply(mutation).get()

// Generated: typed property accessors on Mutator<Address>
var Mutator<Address>.street
    get() = get().street
    set(v) = modifyIfChanged(get().street, v) { it.copy(street = v) }

var Mutator<Address>.city
    get() = get().city
    set(v) = modifyIfChanged(get().city, v) { it.copy(city = v) }

var Mutator<Address>.zip
    get() = get().zip
    set(v) = modifyIfChanged(get().zip, v) { it.copy(zip = v) }

// Generated: collection mutators
fun List<Address>.mutator() = mutator(child = { mutator() })
fun Set<Address>.mutator() = mutator(child = { mutator() })
fun <K> Map<K, Address>.mutator() = mutator(child = { mutator() })`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>For nested <code>@Mutable</code> properties (like <code>Person.address</code>), KSP generates a sub-mutator with
        <code>onChange</code> propagation:</p>

    <Code code={`// Generated: sub-mutator with automatic back-propagation
val Mutator<Person>.address
    get() = get().address.mutator()
        .onChange { address -> modifyValue { get().copy(address = address) } }`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>This is the magic: when you set <code>mutator.address.street = "..."</code>, the address mutator notifies the
        person mutator via <code>onChange</code>, which rebuilds the person with the new address. All of this happens
        automatically.</p>

    <h2>Controlling discovery with <code>deep</code></h2>

    <p>By default, <code>@Mutable</code> recursively discovers all referenced types and generates mutators for them. You
        can control this with the <code>deep</code> parameter:</p>

    <Code code={`// Default: deep = true — discovers and generates mutators for all referenced types
@Mutable
data class Person(val address: Address)
// Address gets a mutator too, even without its own @Mutable annotation

// Shallow: deep = false — only this class gets a mutator
@Mutable(deep = false)
data class Order(
    val id: String,
    val meta: ExternalConfig,    // simple get/set (ExternalConfig has no mutator)
    val address: Address,        // .mutator() accessor (Address IS @Mutable)
)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>With <code>deep = false</code>, referenced types only get <code>.mutator()</code> accessors if they are
        independently marked <code>@Mutable</code> (or pulled in by another <code>deep = true</code> class). Otherwise,
        they get simple get/set accessors — like a <code>String</code> or <code>Int</code>.</p>

    <p>This is useful when you want to make a class with external types mutable without pulling in the entire type
        graph.
        Conversely, if you need mutators for external types not in your codebase, use the trigger pattern:</p>

    <Code code={`// Trigger mutator generation for types you don't own
@Mutable(deep = true)
data class TriggerMutators(
    val ext: SomeExternalLibraryType,
)
// SomeExternalLibraryType now gets a mutator generated`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Excluding types with <code>@NotMutable</code></h2>

    <p>Use <code>@NotMutable</code> to explicitly prevent mutator generation for a type, even if it would be discovered
        transitively:</p>

    <Code code={`@NotMutable
data class Secret(val key: String, val value: String)

@Mutable
data class Config(
    val name: String,
    val secret: Secret,  // simple get/set — Secret is @NotMutable
)`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p><code>@NotMutable</code> takes priority over transitive discovery. The property gets a simple get/set accessor
        instead of a <code>.mutator()</code> accessor.</p>

    <div class="not-prose mt-8 flex gap-4">
        <a href="/ultra/mutator/core-concepts"
           class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
            Core concepts &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

</DocsLayout>
